-Comté, France":"Grancey-le-Château, Côte-d'Or, Bourgogne, Frankrijk","Dijon, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France":"Dijon, Côte-d'Or, Bourgogne, Frankrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1265–Aft 1328":"about 1265–after 1328","1255–1341":"1255–1341","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1265–1328":"1265–1328","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1260–1329":"1260–1329","1290–1357":"1290–1357","1300–1389":"1300–1389","1235–1297":"1235–1297","1240–1300":"1240–1300","1297":"1297","1341":"1341","1296":"1296","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","Abt 1329":"about 1329","Aft 1328":"after 1328","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1357":"1357","1235":"1235","1389":"1389","1300":"1300","Abt 1265":"about 1265","1255":"1255","1265":"1265","1320":"1320","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Grancey-le-Château-Neuvelle, Côte-d'Or, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, France":"Grancey-le-Château, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France","Dijon, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France":"Dijon, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Grancey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Pegeen.","Irish (Roscommon): variant of   Glancy  , from <b>Mag Fhlannchaidh</b> (see   Clancy  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Glancy","meanings":["Irish (Roscommon and Leitrim): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Fhlannchaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Flannchadh</i>’ (see   Clancy  )."]}]},{"name":"Eudes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Eade  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Eads","meanings":["and Norwegian equivalent of <b>Matthew</b> ."]},{"name":"Eade","meanings":["From the name of the precious stone, a word that reached English from Spanish <i>(piedra de) ijada</i>, which literally means ‘(stone of the) bowels’. It was so called because it was believed to have the magical power of providing protection against disorders of the intestines. The vogue for this word as a given name developed later than that for other gemstone names, possibly because it sounds the same as the vocabulary word denoting a broken-down old horse or a nagging woman. It came to notice in the early 1970s when the daughter of the English rock star  Mick Jagger  was so named, peaking in popularity through the 1990s. In  2002  the name became famous as that of  Jade Goody  (  1981–2009 ), who first attracted public attention as a remarkably cheerful but ill-informed contestant on Channel 4's reality TV show Big Brother."]},{"name":"Edes","meanings":["This name is found as a variant or pet form of   Edith   in Yorkshire from the 15th century onwards. It is recorded as a baptismal name in the 16th century. In present-day use it probably refers to the biblical ‘Garden of Eden’, crew ῾<i>eden</i> ‘place of pleasure’. As a boy's name it may also represent a variant of   Aidan   or a transferred use of a surname, itself derived in the Middle Ages from a given name <i>Edun</i> or <i>Edon</i>. This is of Old English origin, from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>hūn</i> ‘bear cub’."]},{"name":"Edds","meanings":["Pet form of any of several old German names beginning with <i>Ed-</i>. The Elder and Younger <i>Eddas</i> are also the names of two influential Old Icelandic books of Norse myths and poems."]}]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Vivian   and   Vivien ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eudes IV de Grancey was born about 1265, in Grancey-le-Château, Côte-d'Or, Burgundy, France, his father, Guillaume Sire de Grancey, was 32 and his mother, Isabelle de Til-Chatel, was 27. He married Isabelle De Blamont in 1296. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died after 1328."},"et":{"Abt 1265–Aft 1328":"umbes 1265–pärast 1328","1255–1341":"1255–1341","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1265–1328":"1265–1328","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1260–1329":"1260–1329","1290–1357":"1290–1357","1300–1389":"1300–1389","1235–1297":"1235–1297","1240–1300":"1240–1300","1297":"1297","1341":"1341","1296":"1296","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","Abt 1329":"umbes 1329","Aft 1328":"pärast 1328","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1357":"1357","1235":"1235","1389":"1389","1300":"1300","Abt 1265":"umbes 1265","1255":"1255","1265":"1265",